The best approach is to adopt the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it's a well-established library that wraps the entire `System.IO` surface behind mockable interfaces.

## Setup

**1. Install packages:**
```bash
dotnet add <YourProject> package System.IO.Abstractions
dotnet add <YourTestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

**2. Register in DI** (Program.cs / Startup.cs):
```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

**3. Inject `IFileSystem` instead of using statics:**
```csharp
public class ConfigManager(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Load(string path)
        => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public void Save(string path, string content)
        => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public bool EnsureDirectory(string path)
        => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

**4. Test with `MockFileSystem`:**
```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"key\": \"value\"}") }
});

var manager = new ConfigManager(mockFs);

Assert.Equal("{\"key\": \"value\"}", manager.Load("/config.json"));

manager.Save("/output.txt", "hello");
Assert.Equal("hello", mockFs.File.ReadAllText("/output.txt"));

Assert.False(mockFs.Directory.Exists("/nonexistent"));
```

## Why this over a custom wrapper?

| | Custom wrapper | System.IO.Abstractions |
|---|---|---|
| Coverage | Only methods you wrap | Full `System.IO` surface |
| Maintenance | You own it | Community-maintained, battle-tested |
| Test helpers | Write your own mocks | `MockFileSystem` included |

Once you've added the package and DI registration, use the **migrate-static-to-wrapper** skill to bulk-replace all `File.*` / `Directory.*` call sites across your project.
